<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="468" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d468">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">Food Administrator’s File</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador on Special Mission</hi>
                                    (<persName corresp="#p_RERDI1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Reading</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Food
                                    Administrator</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HHC1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Hoover</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-16">
                                        <hi rend="italic">April 16, 1918</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HHC1">Hoover</persName></hi>: I have to-day received a reply to
                                the telegram which was despatched to London after the discussion on
                                Thursday last of your proposals about wheat. I am glad to be able to
                                tell you that the Wheat Executive agree to the supply of 2,000,000
                                bushels of Canadian wheat for the Buffalo mills in May, as a final
                                allocation of Canadian wheat for this cereal year. They say that
                                they are naturally reluctant that the supply of bulk wheat should be
                                reduced, but they warmly appreciate the efforts you are making to
                                increase the supply available for export in the coming months, and
                                are therefore most anxious to assist as far as practicable in the
                                solution of your distribution problem.</p>
                            <p>Yours sincerely,</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_RERDI1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reading</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>